4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Under existing law, guardians ad litem are
6 required to perform certain duties in order to protect
7 the best interests of the child.
8 This bill would further provide for the duties
9 of guardians ad litem, including, but not limited to,
10 regular meetings with children and foster parents,
11 conducting ongoing investigations and review of court
12 cases, review of certain reports related to subject
13 children, and when appropriate, filing pleadings to
14 promote the best interests of children and timely
15 permanent resolution of cases.
16
17
18 A BILL
19 TO BE ENTITLED
20 AN ACT
21
22 Relating to guardians ad litem; to amend Section
23 12-15-304, Code of Alabama 1975; to further provide for the
24 duties of guardians ad litem.
25 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
26 Section 1. Section 12-15-304, Code of Alabama 1975, is
27 amended to read as follows:
28 "§12-15-304
Page 1

"§12-15-304
HB570 INTRODUCED
29 (a) In all dependency and termination of parental
30 rights proceedings, the juvenile court shall appoint a
31 guardian ad litem for a child who is a party to the
32 proceedings and whose primary responsibility shall be to
33 protect the best interests of the child.
34 (b) The guardian ad litem, irrespective of the age of
35 the child, shall:
36 (1) Meet with the child and speak with the child's
37 foster parents before every court hearing, when significant
38 events impact the child, and when the guardian ad litem is
39 apprised of emergencies, except where any such meeting is
40 impracticable due to exigent circumstances; and
41 (2) Explain, in terms understandable to the child, what
42 is expected to happen before, during, and after each juvenile
43 court hearing.
44 (c) The duties of the guardian ad litem shall include,
45 but shall not be limited to, the following:
46 (1) Conduct an ongoing,Irrespective of the age of the
47 child, meet with the child prior to juvenile court hearings
48 and when apprised of emergencies or significant events
49 impacting the child. In addition, the guardian ad litem shall
50 explain, in terms understandable to the child, what is
51 expected to happen before, during, and after each juvenile
52 court hearing.
53 (2) Conduct a thorough, and independent investigation,
54 including the following, at a minimum:
55 a. Face-to-face meetings to observe the child's
56 physical, mental, social, and educational well being.
